subSection.paragraph:
Secondary metabolites are usually biosynthesized as single stereoisomers in nature, but some natural products exist as enantiomers (
Chen et al., 2012
; 
Finefield et al., 2012
; 
Sai et al., 2015
; 
Tian et al., 2016
; 
Xu et al., 2019
; 
Kittakoop, 2019
, 
2020
). As stereocentres in structures often determine biological and pharmaceutical properties together with chemical and physical characteristics, it is very important to chirally separate enantiomers and establish their absolute configurations. Enantiomers can usually be separated by chiral columns, but suitable or new approaches can be used or developed to separate enantiomers with limited amounts. Recently, our group initiated the chemical investigation of desert plant endophytic fungi from Northwest 
China
considering their special bioenvironments and few chemical investigations. A series of new secondary metabolites with diverse biological activities were isolated from this group of fungi (
Li et al., 2018
, 
2020
; 
Song et al., 2019
; 
Tan et al., 2018
, 
2019
; 
Zhang et al., 2018
). Per our ongoing research to mine secondary metabolites with unique structures and potential bioactivities from this special group of fungi, the EtOAc extracts of the endophytic fungus 
Phaeosphaeriaceae
sp. were investigated, which led to the isolation of a novel polyketide-originated secondary metabolite, phaeosphspirone (
1
), and two known pyranonaphthoquinones, herbarin (
2
) and 
O
-methylherbarin (
3
) (
Fig. 1
) (
Paranagama et al., 2007
). A pair of enantiomers (
1
/ 
1
′
) existing in phaeosphspirone were separated by HPLC chromatography after derivatization with Mosher’ s reagents, and the absolute configurations of 
1
/ 
1
′
were simultaneously determined according to Mosher’ s rule. This tandem strategy provides a useful approach for the separation and stereochemical determination of enantiomers with secondary hydroxyl groups. In this report, the structural elucidation, separation, possible biogenetic pathway, and biological activities of these compounds are presented.

The relative configuration of phaeosphspirone was determined by NOE spectra analysis (
Fig. 2
). Upon irradiation with H-3, enhancements of 12-OMe and 1-Me were observed, while irradiation with 12-OMe or 1- Me led to the enhancement of 1-Me and H-3 or H-3 and 12-OMe, respectively. These results confirmed that 1-Me, H-3 and 12-OMe had the same orientation on the furan ring, which established the relative configuration of phaeosphspirone (Fig. S11-S13).

Considering the coisolation of herbarin (
2
) and 
O
-methylherbarin (
3
) from the same fungus and the similar structural features, phaeosphspirone (
1
/ 
1
′
) is likely to be derived from 
2
with a pyranonaphthoquinone core skeleton. Isotopic enrichment experiments revealed that pyranonaphthoquinone scorpinone coisolated with 
2
from the same fungus originating from polyketide biosynthesis (
Van Wagoner et al., 2008
), and Tudzynski et al. investigated the biosynthetic polyketide (PKS) gene cluster of fusarubin, a pyranonaphthoquinone analogue similar to scorpinone (
Cox, 2017
). This evidence supported that phaeosphspirone, as a heptaketide, was biosynthesized from a PKS pathway similar to the metabolites mentioned above. Polyketides (PKSs) can be further divided into the following three subtypes: nonreduced (NR), partially reduced (PR), and highly reduced (HR), which are biosynthesized from the corresponding mega-synthase NR-PKS synthases (NR-PKSs), PR-PKSs and HR-PKSs, respectively (Fig. S18) (
Cox, 2017
).
